Reading this thread there seems to be some confusion between the standard deviation of the mean of a sample, and the standard deviation of the underlying distribution of the sample. Specifically, if s is the standard deviation of the distribution of the sample (150000 in the original post), then s/sqrt(n) is the standard deviation of the mean (150000/sqrt(3650)=2482 in the original post). The mean is normally distributed (at least for large n) for any reasonable distribution by the central limit theorem, and hence the 95% confidence interval of the mean is mean +/- 1.96*standard deviation of the mean, or roughly mean +/- 2*standard deviation of the mean (that's approximately 33500 +/-2*2482 in the example). The standard deviation of the mean is also often called the standard error. Finally, logically if the chosen y-value falls above the confidence interval then there is only a 2.5% chance that the mean of the sample is above the chosen y-value, not 5%. That's because there's another 2.5% below the confidence interval. So if one wanted to be 5% sure, then one should use the 90% confidence interval (but please note that the instructions do NOT say that).

The confidence interval (in %) is the range in which we believe the true POPULATION mean will lie x times out of 100. So a 95% confidence interval of a mean of the sample is the range of values that 95 times out of 100 we expect the mean of the population to lie within. The mean of the population is unknown to us; we know from the weak law of large numbers that the sample mean as we are used to calculating it is indeed an unbiased and consistent estimator of the population mean, since the sample mean and the population mean will converge in probabilities as the sample size tends to infinity. This is the notion of statistical consistency (if anyone has studied stats or metrics), and it is how we prove consistency of an estimator. The standard deviation of the SAMPLE is different from the standard error of the mean. The standard error of the mean is a fancy way of saying the standard deviation of the MEAN, not the standard deviation of the data. We use the sample standard deviation to construct the standard errors of the mean to make some sort of inference about the population mean.
